## What is Spark
- Open source
- distributed processing system
- for big data

used for:
- batch processing
- interactive queries
- real time analytics
- ML
- graph processing
## Architecture

![](data:image/png;base64,)

processing:

- RDDs distributed over (worker) machines
- transformations and actions done in parallel within those machines
- results sent to driver in the final step
- unused RDDs removed from memory

## Spark vs Hadoop

Hadoop MapReduce requires disk IO at every step while Spark does processing in-memory and reuses data across multiple parallel ops

## RDDs vs DataFrames

RDDs: Resilient Distributed Datasets

- immutable data distributed across multiple servers
- unstructured
- low level API

DataFrame

- structured columns
- high level API for actions and transformations

## Transformations & Actions

Transformations

- e.g. map, order, groupBy, filter, join, select, cache
- lazy operations

Actions

- e.g. show, count, save, collect
- triggers spark to compute a result from a series of transformations

## DAG

Spark creates a DAG representing all the RDDs and how they'll be transformed

- transformations construct the graph, actions trigger computations on it

![](data:image/png;base64,)

**Narrow Dependencies**
Each partition of the parent RDD is used by at most 1 partition of the child RDD (injective)
e.g. map, flatmap, filter, contains

**Wide Dependencies**
each partition of parent RDD is used by multiple partitions of the child RDD
e.g. reduceByKey, groupBy, orderBy

Stages

- Consecutive narrow deps grped tgt as stages
- within stages, spark performs consec transformations on same machines
- across stages, data needs to be shuffled
	- data is written to the target worker node's DISK
- to improve performance, need to minimise shuffling

## Fault Tolerance
- Uses the lineage approach
- If worker node goes down,
	1. replace with new worker node
	2. use DAG to recompute lost data

## Spark  + YARN
YARN (Yet Another Resource Negotiator): Cluster management technology

**Architecture**
![[Pasted image 20240810135626.png]]
![[Pasted image 20240810140220.png]]
**Workflow**
- Spark app is submitted to the resource manager
- Spark driver is run in the ApplicationMaster (inside one of the YARN worker nodes)
- ApplicationMaster negotiates resources from ResourceManager
	- each app has 1 application master
	- initial resources for the appmaster is negotiated by the Application Master in the ResourceManager
	- subsequent resource allocation is by the scheduler, based on scheduling policies
- Spark executors run in the allocated containers on the worker nodes
